Most songs carry 2 distinct copyrights: one for song composition (arrangement of music and lyrics) and one for tangible sound recording of  music (known as the "master"). Most traditional pre-streaming contracts gave record labels the sound recording, musicians publishing rights.

Each dollar of revenue Spotify earns, 58.5 cents go to owner of a song's sound recording (usually a record label), Spotify keeps 29.38 cents, 6.12 cents to whoever owns publishing rights (usually the songwriter) and 6 cents to mechanical rights (often owned by the songwriter).
